Controlling Application Permissions with Security Context Constraints
Objectives
Create service accounts and apply permissions, and manage security context constraints.
1. Controlling Application Permissions with Security Context Constraints (SCC)
What is Security Context Constraints (SCC)?
Security Context Constraints (SCC) is a security mechanism in OpenShift that controls what a pod is allowed to do on the host system.
In simple words:
👉 SCC limits the permissions of containers so they cannot harm the host or the cluster.
It protects the node (host machine) from malicious or unsafe containers.
________________________________________
Why SCC is Important
Containers downloaded from public registries may try to:
•	Run as root user
•	Access host filesystem
•	Use privileged ports
•	Use special Linux capabilities
If not restricted, this can compromise the cluster.
So OpenShift applies SCC policies to control container permissions.
________________________________________
2. What SCC Controls
SCC controls access to host resources such as:
1️⃣ Running privileged containers
Allows containers to run with root-level host access.
Example:
privileged: true
This gives container full control over the node, which is dangerous.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Extra Linux Capabilities
Linux capabilities are special permissions like:
•	NET_ADMIN
•	SYS_ADMIN
These allow containers to control network or system operations.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Host directories as volumes
Containers normally cannot access host filesystem.
Example restricted path:
/etc
/var
/root
SCC decides whether container can mount host directories.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Changing SELinux context
OpenShift uses SELinux security labeling.
SCC controls whether containers can change their SELinux context.
________________________________________
5️⃣ Changing User ID (UID)
Containers normally run with random UID for security.
Some containers require specific UID (like 1000).
SCC decides if this is allowed.
________________________________________
3. Default SCCs in OpenShift
You can list SCCs with this command:
oc get scc
Example output:
anyuid
hostaccess
hostnetwork
node-exporter
nonroot
privileged
restricted
Each SCC has different security levels.
________________________________________
Important SCC Types
1️⃣ restricted (Default)
Most secure.
Pods:
•	run with random UID
•	cannot run as root
•	cannot access host resources
Used by most applications.
________________________________________
2️⃣ nonroot
Containers cannot run as root user.
Must run with UID ≠ 0.
________________________________________
3️⃣ anyuid
Allows containers to run as any user ID, including root.
Used when applications require specific UID.
________________________________________
4️⃣ privileged
Most powerful.
Allows containers to:
•	access host
•	run privileged operations
•	use host devices
⚠ Very dangerous if misused.
________________________________________
4. Checking Which SCC a Pod Uses
Command:
oc describe pod POD_NAME -n NAMESPACE
Example:
oc describe pod console-5df4fcbb47-67c52 -n openshift-console
Then filter SCC:
grep scc
Example output:
openshift.io/scc: restricted
Meaning:
👉 Pod is using restricted SCC
________________________________________
5. Why Some Containers Fail with Restricted SCC
Some container images require:
•	specific user ID
•	root privileges
•	privileged ports (<1024)
Example:
Port 80 requires root permission.
But restricted SCC runs containers with random UID, so the application fails.
________________________________________
6. Checking Which SCC Can Run a Pod
Command:
oc get deployment deployment-name -o yaml | \
oc adm policy scc-subject-review -f -
Purpose:
✔ Shows which SCCs are compatible with the deployment
________________________________________
7. Solution: Use Service Account with SCC
To run containers with different SCC permissions, OpenShift uses Service Accounts.
Flow:
Pod → Service Account → SCC
Meaning:
Service account receives SCC permission.
________________________________________
Step 1 — Create Service Account
Command:
oc create serviceaccount service-account-name
Example:
oc create serviceaccount myserviceaccount
If creating in another namespace:
oc create serviceaccount myserviceaccount -n myproject
________________________________________
Step 2 — Assign SCC to Service Account
Command:
oc adm policy add-scc-to-user SCC -z service-account
Example:
oc adm policy add-scc-to-user anyuid -z myserviceaccount
Meaning:
Give anyuid SCC to the service account.
⚠ Only cluster administrators can run this command.
________________________________________
Step 3 — Apply Service Account to Deployment
Command:
oc set serviceaccount deployment/deployment-name service-account-name
Example:
oc set serviceaccount deployment/myapp myserviceaccount
Result:
•	Deployment redeploys pods
•	Pods now run with new SCC
________________________________________
8. Privileged Containers
Some applications need deep access to host system.
Example:
•	S2I builder containers
•	monitoring agents
•	storage drivers
•	networking tools
These containers require:
privileged SCC
Privileged containers can:
•	access host kernel
•	modify system
•	control network
•	access devices
⚠ This is high security risk.
Therefore only specific service accounts should have this access.
________________________________________
9. Important Security Warning
Giving less restrictive SCC like:
•	anyuid
•	privileged
can:
❌ reduce cluster security
❌ allow containers to escape isolation
❌ expose host system
So always follow:
✔ Principle of least privilege
